Remember this? https://pastebin.com/nCwti01C

On May 15th, Greg Miller and Greg Jaffe of the Washington Post broke a story that heavily implied Trump damaged national security by leaking information in a conversation with the Russian foreign minister and ambassador:


https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/trump-revealed-highly-classified-information-to-russian-foreign-minister-and-ambassador/2017/05/15/530c172a-3960-11e7-9e48-c4f199710b69_story.html


The next morning, National Security Advisor H.R. McMaster held a press briefing asserting that "the premise of the article is false":


http://www.realclearpolitics.com/video/2017/05/16/mcmaster_national_security_put_at_risk_by_leaks_like_washington_post_story.html
	What I'm saying is really the premise of that article is false, that in any way the president had a conversation that was inappropriate or that resulted in any kind of lapse in national security.

	...in the context of that that discussion, what the president discussed with the foreign minister was wholly appropriate to that conversation and is consistent with the routine sharing of information between the president and any leaders with whom he's engaged.


https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/trump-revealed-highly-classified-information-to-russian-foreign-minister-and-ambassador/2017/05/15/530c172a-3960-11e7-9e48-c4f199710b69_story.html
	Most alarmingly, officials said, Trump revealed the city in the Islamic State’s territory where the U.S. intelligence partner detected the threat.

	The Post is withholding most plot details, including the name of the city, at the urging of officials who warned that revealing them would jeopardize important intelligence capabilities.


http://www.realclearpolitics.com/video/2017/05/16/mcmaster_national_security_put_at_risk_by_leaks_like_washington_post_story.html
	QUESTION: ...Did the president reveal a city? I mean, the spin is that the president revealed the name of the city, and that gave away information that undermined an ally.

	MCMASTER: OK, I will answer that.

	OK, so, all of you are very familiar with the threat from ISIS. All of you are very familiar with the territory it controls. If you were to say, "Hey, from where do you think a threat might come from territory that ISIS controls?," you would probably be able to name a few cities, I would think.

	And so it was -- it was nothing that you would not know from open source reporting in terms of a source of concern. And it had -- it had all to do with operations that are already ongoing, had been made public for months.


Specifically, McMaster shot-down the implication of the Washington Post story that Trump's disclosure was inappropriate and damaged national security. He did not confirm or deny that Trump revealed classified information (and I'm not sure if he legally can). But it is implied that Trump revealed the name of the ISIS-controlled city where Israel "detected the threat," and that this disclosure was appropriate and innocuous.

Yet a few hours later, a number of public figures and journalists (including one of the authors of the WaPo article) were ready to hit the press essentially (or directly) calling McMaster a liar:


https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/a-new-role-for-mcmaster-trumps-shield/2017/05/16/c49bdcd0-3a60-11e7-a058-ddbb23c75d82_story.html
