What makes them so sure? McMaster's main point was that the conversation didn't damage national security, contradicting the WaPo article. And unlike the WaPo authors, McMaster was actually present for the conversation and is qualified to judge national security breaches. And McMaster has a reputation for integrity. So why assume he is a liar?

What's interesting is that McMaster has a unique role in Trump's cabinet: he is one of the few cabinet members to improve our national security situation. Remember this timeline: https://pastebin.com/nCwti01C Flynn was compromised, and McMaster undid his changes to the NSC, moving the suspicious people Flynn brought on to other positions. And McMaster is also unique in that he was not brought-on by Trump's transition team, and Pence, who's selection as VP appears to have alarmed some Trump associates (http://time.com/4409330/donald-trump-mike-pence-vice-president-2/), reportedly "played a role" in picking McMaster.

On top of this, there are reports that McMaster has fallen out of favor with Trump, or that Trump even intends to fire him:


http://www.newsweek.com/trump-mcmaster-israel-russia-fired-national-security-adviser-jared-kushner-616735
	Is H.R. McMaster, the White House national security adviser, on the way out? By some signs, he is: President Donald Trump not only excluded him from a key meeting with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and his national security adviser Monday night in Jerusalem, he was kept “outside the King David [Hotel] room during the course of the entire meeting,” according to an eye-catching Israeli account.

	Taken alone, the perceived shaming wouldn’t amount to much: Trump has a habit of slighting his aides in public. But the incident came only days after a report in The New York Times that McMaster had fallen out of favor with the president. Trump had “complained that General McMaster talks too much in meetings,” and “the president has referred to him as ‘a pain,’” The Times said in a report that was not challenged by the White House. By the time Trump left Israel for his meeting in Rome with the Pope, right-wing news sites closely allied with the so-called “nationalist” wing of the White House were serving up full throated criticism of McMaster, a distinguished Army general.

	...Another writer at the liberal-leaning Foreign Policy web site quoted from McMaster’s book, Dereliction of Duty, to suggest he risked grave injury to his reputation if he stuck around much longer.


Compounding this, as the Newsweek article points out, some of the "alt-right" press has started attacking McMaster, calling him soft on "Islamic terrorism" and spreading conspiracy theories alleging his involvement in plots to manipulate the President with fake intelligence reports.

Ostensibly, firing McMaster would be disastrous for Trump's image: his administration is under investigation for collusion with Russia, he just fired his FBI Director, and the rest of his top advisors are all embroiled in some sort of Russia-related scandal. And McMaster appears to be one of the few (if only) advisors to counter Russia's influence in the White House and disagree with Trump: Trump overrode McMaster's decision to remove Ezra Cohen-Watnick from his position as Senior Intelligence Director, which troubled the CIA, after Cohen-Watnick appealed to Kushner and Bannon. Reportedly, Cohen-Watnick went on to search for intelligence intercepts to validate President Trump's wiretapping claims. With this being the only major disagreement between McMaster and Trump in the press, firing McMaster would raise even more questions about President Trump's honesty, relationship with Russia, and commitment to national security. Firing McMaster would not only remove the only key Trump advisor who is both sane and free of ties to Russia, it would be a public scandal nearly as big as Trump's firing of Yates or Comey.

Or, would be--except the recent press reports accusing McMaster of being a liar and calling for his resignation have created the perception that he deserves to be fired or even wants to be fired. Since, in the abstract, firing someone who deserves it or wants it isn't surprising, these reports have mitigated any scandal that would result from firing McMaster, at least in the eyes of the public. They are making it easier for Trump to fire McMaster.

Yet, after the Washington Post released an article saying that Jared Kushner, among other things, wanted to set up a secret back-channel with the Russians (https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/russian-ambassador-told-moscow-that-kushner-wanted-secret-communications-channel-with-kremlin/2017/05/26/520a14b4-422d-11e7-9869-bac8b446820a_story.html), some in print and social media took to beating-up on McMaster again:


