The general theme of these reports is that McMaster told the press WaPo's Kushner story didn't bother him and has therefore lost all credibility. But that's not what he said:


https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JFE1pdMv4yY

https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-russia-kushner-idUSKBN18N0NA
	Reporter: Question for General McMaster--I know you said you didn't want to address this, but you are the National Security Advisor, so, you know, I think we're all wondering why someone who's now a senior administration official would want or need a back-channel to Russia, and from you view what the security concerns are surrounding that, if it's appropriate to set something like that up?

	McMaster: No it's not something that I've in any way been involved with or have any knowledge of.

	Cohn: We--We're not gonna comment on Jared. We're just not gonna comment on it.

	Reporter: General, generally speaking General would you be concerned if somebody on the National Security Council or in this administration were to seek a back-channel communication system with the Russian embassy? And with the Kremlin? Would that generally concern you, not to even address Kushner specifically, but in general terms?

	McMaster: No. I mean we have back-channel communications with a number of countries. So generally speaking, about back-channel communications, what that allows you do to is communicate in a discrete manner. So it doesn't pre-dispose you to any sort of content of the conversation or anything. So no, I would not be concerned about it.

	Reporter: So you're not concerned General? You're not concerned.

McMaster said that generally speaking, (and ignoring all the strange details of the Kushner story), a back-channel between Trump and Russia would not concern him. McMaster implies back-channel communications between states are normal and common, which is correct:


https://muse.jhu.edu/book/12968
	Wanis-St. John takes on the question of whether the complex and often perilous secret negotiations between principal parties prove to be instrumental paths to reconciliation or rather roadblocks that disrupt the process. Using the Palestinian-Israeli peace process as a framework, the author focuses on the uses and misuses of "back channel" negotiations. He discusses how top-level PLO and Israeli government officials have often resorted to secret negotiation channels even when there were designated, acknowledged negotiation teams already at work. Intense scrutiny by the media, pressure from constituents, and the reactions of the public all become severe constraints to the process, causing leaders to seek out such back channels. The impact of these secret talks within the peace process over time has largely been unexplored.


http://www.wbur.org/hereandnow/2014/02/17/lincoln-peace-conference
	Critics say the U.S. should never negotiate with a country like Iran. But as the Obama administration and other members of the U.N. Security Council resume talks with Tehran this week, a new book argues that negotiations with your enemy can be the best path.

	The book looks back to a secret peace conference during the late stages of the Civil War when President Abraham Lincoln spoke in person with Confederate representatives on the presidential steamboat River Queen, the Air Force One of her day.


http://www.npr.org/2014/10/01/352775195/secret-talks-and-back-channels-pervaded-u-s-relationship-with-cuba
	For five decades, the official U.S. policy on Cuba was one of silence. But the real U.S. relationship with Havana involved secret negotiations that started with President Kennedy in 1963, even after his embargo against the island nation, say the authors of the new book Back Channel to Cuba. In fact, nearly every U.S. administration for the past 50 years has engaged in some sort of dialogue with the Cuban government, they say.


For any President, the back-channel itself isn't interesting, it's what they say that may or may not be concerning. As McMaster pointed out, a back-channel "doesn't pre-dispose you to any sort of content of the conversation or anything."  McMaster, either not knowing or not caring that his words would be used against him, simply answered the question straight.

So one has to wonder, why are media figures attacking him? Even for the few reports that pointed-out he didn't comment on the Kushner story specifically, many or most insinuated McMaster was involved in some kind of conspiracy to cover for Trump (e.g. https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2017/05/27/trump-adviser-i-would-not-be-concerned-about-a-russia-back-channel-irrespective-of-kushner/). And these reports were once again followed with calls for McMaster to resign:


